Feature Elimination¶

The purpose of this analysis is to build a neural network classifier to determine customers will leave the bank in the next 6 months. Given this, various features are not required for the purpose of this analysis. These include:

  1. Row Number - the index already accounts for this, so we can drop this row

  2. Customer ID - we can drop this variable given that it is just an ID representing the specific individual.

  3. Suranme - the surname of the individual will not assit in determining if an individual will leave the bank.

Surname is also of 'object' data type. In order to proceed and implement this into a nerural network we would need to use one hot encoding to numerically determine their class. This would in turn lead to an excessive amount of columns/variables for the analysis. I do not consider these variables to be key in predicting as to whether an individual will leave the bank or not. Given this, I will drop these variables.

Summary Overview¶

Reviewing the data helped us gain some initial insight:

Looking at the data info, there does not look to be any null values, as there are 10,000 entries across all the variables.

The isna() function helped confirm this for us.

There are no duplicates within the data.

Referring to the statistical summary of the refinned data set, there does not appear to be much of a variance between the mean and the median between a lot of our variables. The Balance feature does look to have a mean value considerably less than the mean. This will result in a left skew in the distribution of this variable.

There does look to be outliers for estimated age, salary and balance, given there is a large difference between the 3rd quartile and the max value. These outliers may need to be treated, as outliers may effect the bias of these variables. We will take a deeper look into this in the Exploratory Data Analysis section (EDA).

Credit Scors also appears to has some outliers, as the min is considerable less than the first quartile. This will lead to a left skew in the distribution.

Number of products has a min value of 1, implying that all customers within the dataset have at least one account with the bank.

HasCrCard and IsActiveMemeber are binary variables as they take a value of either 1 or 0.

def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15, 10), bins=None):
    """Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (9,8))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, color="orange"
    ) if bins else sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, color="tab:cyan"
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        np.mean(feature), color="purple", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        np.median(feature), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.
# This will help provide observations of some of the categorical data types. 

def perc_on_bar(plot, feature):
    """
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in hue parameter
    """
    total = len(feature)  # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = "{:.1f}%".format(
            100 * p.get_height() / total
        )  # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()  # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size=12)  # annotate the percantage
    plt.show()  # show the plot

def stacked_plot(x):
    sns.set(palette="nipy_spectral")
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(x, data["Exited"], margins=True)
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(x, data['Exited'], normalize="index")
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.legend(loc='upper center', bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, 1.03), ncol=2)
    plt.show()

Data Balance & Correlations¶

There is significant imbalance within the data. Roughly 80% of customers have stayed with the bank, leaving roughly 20% that have actually churned/left the bank. Working with an imbalanced data set can prove to be very challenging for building predicitve models, as it can lead to frequency bias. This means the model will learn more from the data within the majority class i.e. the customers that have not churned. Action may need to be taken when building the models in order to cater to this.

There does not appear to be any strong correlation within the data at hand. Hoever it is worth noting some of the correlations at hand. The number of products appears to be negatively correlated with balance. There is also positive correlation between age and customers that have exited, but it is not a strong correlation.

If there was any noticable mutilcolinearity among the independent variables, we would have to look to reassess and potentially drop additional features. When this correlation is evident it can cause a problem because independent variables should be independent of one another. If the degree of correlation between variables is high enough, it can cause problems when you fit the model and interpret the results. Howeveve, this action is not required for this analysis. In addition, there are no significant/extreme outliers among the variables, so no treatment is required.

Feature Conversion¶

Bothe Geography and Gender and currently categorical variables. To utilise these columns, well need to use one hot encoding to convert to numerical data. Using one hot encoding, additioanl columns will be created (one for each class). However, we will take the approach of dropping the first of the newly created columns. For example, with gender there will initially be 2 columns (1 for males and 1 for females). A 1 for male will return a 0 for female and therefore there is no need for both columns. This concept also transfers to geography.

Rescale the Data¶

Prior to developing the neural network model, we will need to scale the data. This is ensure that the variables are somewhat comparable in terms of the units measured. We want to ensure that variables with the highest units are not considered the dominant features by default. For example, in the data set the Esitmated Salary and Balance are considerably higher that some of the other variables, in terms of units measured. Differences in the scales across input variables may increase the difficulty of the problem being modeled. Large input values can result in a model that learns large weight values. A model with large weight values is often unstable, meaning that it may suffer from poor performance during learning and sensitivity to input values resulting in higher generalization error.

Scaling the data is therefore always advisable in the pre-processing stage. We will use the standardscaler() function to scale the data.

In [38]:
#Standardizing the data

# Define the scaler

# Scale the train set
X_train = scaler.transform(X_train)

# Scale the test set
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

Model building¶

Neural network (NN)¶

Model-1

We will use a simple NN made of 5 fully-connected layers with ReLu activation. The NN takes a vector of length 11 as input. This represents the information related to each variable. The final layer will output a probability distribution (sigmoid activation function) and classify either as not churned (0) or churned (1). a dropout step is included to prevent overfitting. Dropout

Dropout is a regularization technique for neural network models proposed by Srivastava, et al. in their 2014 paper Dropout: A Simple Way to Prevent Neural Networks from Overfitting. Dropout is a technique where randomly selected neurons are ignored during training. They are dropped-out randomly.

In [39]:
#initialize the model
# used to create the model. We are instantiating the model here. Creates an empty model for us. 
# we will begin to add layers to this model.
model = Sequential()

Adding layers [layers and activations]¶

Keras layers can be added to the model

Adding layers are like stacking lego blocks one by one

It should be noted that as this is a classification problem, sigmoid layer (softmax for multi-class problems) should be added.

In [40]:
# This adds the input layer (by specifying input dimension) AND the first hidden layer (units)
model.add(Dense(units=16, input_dim = 11,activation='relu'))   # input of 11 columns as shown above
# hidden layer
model.add(Dense(units=24,activation='relu'))
#Adding Dropout to prevent overfitting 
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(24,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dense(24,activation='relu'))
# Adding the output layer
# Notice that we do not need to specify input dim. 
# we have an output of 1 node, which is the the desired dimensions of our output (exit or not)
# We use the sigmoid because we want probability outcomes
model.add(Dense(1,activation='sigmoid'))                        # binary classification exit or not

Training [Forward pass and Backpropagation]¶

Training the model

While training the model we will make use of additioanl hyperparameters that are used in forward pass and backpropagation learning algorithm.

There parameters are:

Batches: this refers to the number of samples we decide to split the data into, prior to updating the internal model parameters. The batch is commonly completed while training the model. At the end of the batch, the predictions are compared to the expected output variables and an error is calculated. From this error, the update algorithm is used to improve the model, e.g. move down along the error gradient. Common batch sizes used are 16, 32, 64.

Epochs: the number of epochs defined refers to number of times the learning algorithm will work through the entire training dataset. For each epoch defined the model has oppurtuniy to update the internal model parameters and learn from the data. As the validation loss decreases for each epoch defined, this implies that the model is improving and learning from the data. Given this, it is common for there to be a large number of epochs deinfed (from hundreds to thousands).

Model evaluation criterion¶

The main concern to the bank is a model that will make incorrect predictions. There are 2 primary incorrect predictions that the model can make.

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a customer will leave and the customer does not leave

  2. Predicting a customer will not leave and the customer does in fact leave the bank

Which case is more important?¶

The main loss to the the bank would be a model that predicts that the customer will not leave the bank but they do in fact leave. The overall result to the bank would be a loss of customers and hence a loss of income to the bank. In the case that the customer does not leave, this would not result in a substantial loss of income, as the individual would still be a customer for the bank. Therefore, given that the bank is concerned are being able to correctly predict when a customer will leave the bank, they will want to reduce the number of false negatives.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negative?¶

The bank would want Recall to be maximized. The greater the recall the higher the chances of minimizing false negatives (and maximizing true positives). Hence, the focus should be on increasing recall and minimizing the false negatives or in other words identifying the True Positives(i.e. the bank can better identify the customers the will leave the bank).

We will define a confusion matrix function that will allow us to easily compute the performance results across different models¶

In [47]:
def make_confusion_matrix(cf,
                          group_names=None,
                          categories='auto',
                          count=True,
                          percent=True,
                          cbar=True,
                          xyticks=True,
                          xyplotlabels=True,
                          sum_stats=True,
                          figsize=None,
                          cmap='Blues',
                          title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    '''


    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names)==cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])


    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        #Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy  = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

        #if it is a binary confusion matrix, show some more stats
        if len(cf)==2:
            #Metrics for Binary Confusion Matrices
            precision = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[:,1])
            recall    = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[1,:])
            f1_score  = 2*precision*recall / (precision + recall)
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}\nPrecision={:0.3f}\nRecall={:0.3f}\nF1 Score={:0.3f}".format(
                accuracy,precision,recall,f1_score)
        else:
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}".format(accuracy)
    else:
        stats_text = ""


    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize==None:
        #Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks==False:
        #Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories=False


    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(cf,annot=box_labels,fmt="",cmap=cmap,cbar=cbar,xticklabels=categories,yticklabels=categories)

    if xyplotlabels:
        plt.ylabel('True label')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted label' + stats_text)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(stats_text)
    
    if title:
        plt.title(title)

Auc-ROC Curve & Optimal Threshold¶

We will use the AUD-ROC curve to further evaluate the performance of the model and help determine the optimal threshold to use.

The AUC - ROC curve is a performance measurement that is used for classification problems. The ROC is the probibility curve and the AUC measures the degree of separability of classes. It tells how much the model is capable of distinguishing between classes. The higher the AUC the better the performance of the model, as it allows us to conclude that the model is good at distinguishing betweem each class. The y-axis is the True Positive Rate or the Recall and the x-axis is the False postive rate.

The curve will be built using a range of thresholds on the test set, creating the ROC Curve. We can see that there are a number of points or thresholds close to the top-left of the plot. Determining the optimal threshold will then be required. Determining the optimial threshold can be difficult as there may be various similar thresholds. We will use the geometric mean or known as G-mean to help determine this. The G-Mean is the gerometric mean of Specificity /recall and Sensitivity (true postiives). It is considered to be an unbiased metric for imbalanced classifications, which is what we are currently presented with.

In [53]:
# Calculate the G-mean
gmean = np.sqrt(true_postitive_rate * (1 - false_positive_rate))

# Find the optimal threshold
index = np.argmax(gmean)
thresholdOpt = round(thresholds[index], ndigits = 4)
gmeanOpt = round(gmean[index], ndigits = 4)
fprOpt = round(false_positive_rate[index], ndigits = 4)
tprOpt = round(true_postitive_rate[index], ndigits = 4)
print('Best Threshold: {} with G-Mean: {}'.format(thresholdOpt, gmeanOpt))
print('FPR: {}, TPR: {}'.format(fprOpt, tprOpt))

# Create data viz
plotnine.options.figure_size = (8, 4.8)

    geom_point(aes(x = 'FPR',

                   y = tprOpt),

    geom_line(aes(x = 'FPR',
                  y = 'TPR'))+

Comment on Model Performance¶

Train and Valiation loss¶

Evidence of overfitting is evident from the training loss. Referring to the graph, the training loss continues to decrease sharply att the end. In addition, the validation loss is higher than the training loss and there are fluctuations with the validation loss. These are all evidence that our model is overfitting.

Confusion Matrix Insights¶

Looking at the results of the neural network, the model has a realtively low recall (47%)and a higher percentage of false negtives than than True postives. Given that we are looking to maximize the recall and hence minmize the false negatives the results of the neural model are relatively poor.

The initial poor results are driven by the high imbalance that we initially have discussed within the data. Roughly 80% of the customers have stayed with the bank, and 0 is the dominant classe i.e. a customer that has not left. Thus, this can and has led to overfitting of the dominant class at the training stage.

There ar various methods that can be used to deal with the imbalnce of a data set, such as resampling the data (using SMOTE upsampling and downsampling methods), as well as developing customized versions of the algorithm. However, one of the more simply approach is to change the decsion threshold. Using the AUC_ROC is one method as such, as already discussed. The plot summarizes the behavior of a model by calculating the false positive rate and true positive rate for a set of predictions by the model under different thresholds. Each threshold is a point on the plot and the points are connected to form a curve. A classifier that has no skill (e.g. predicts the majority class under all thresholds) will be represented by a diagonal line from the bottom left to the top right.

Insights from the AUC-ROC Curve¶

When looking at the AUC-ROC curve, our main concern is the area under the curve. With an AUC of 0.825 this could be considered realtively good results, as this implies that the model is good at differentiating between customers that have churned and customers that have stayed i.e. 82.5% chance the model will be able to distinguish between the 2.

Using the AUC-ROC curve is quite useful as we can determine the level of seperability within the data and it helps us convert probabilites into a specific class i.e. whether a customer has churned or not. It is a useful tool for understanding the trade-off for different thresholds. However, given that we require specific class lables from our model, then the optimal threshold would be of more value to us. This would be a threshold on the curve that is closest to the top-left of the plot. It can be difficuly to determine this exact point by simply looking at the ROC curve. Usig the G-Mean to determine this optimal point. The results from the geometric mean imply that the optimal threshhold is 0.2838. A low G-Score will indicate poor performance in the classification of the positive class. Anything beneath this point will be categorized as a minor class (i.e. churned) when its probability is lower than this point and vice versa.

Conclusion:¶

Although the AUC-ROC curves are useful, they can also be over optimistic when there is a severe class imbalance. Curremtly, while only 115 customers are wrongly predicted as having churned, the model only detects 9.65% of the churned customers. As a consequence 218 churned customers are not detected (False Negatives).

Model Improvements¶

Let's try another architecture to get the better Recall¶

There are some basic Hyperparameters which can help to get the better model performance.

Early stopping:¶

As previously mentioned there is evidence of overfitting given the results of the validations loss (there are decreases followed by increases within the graph). Early stopping is a method that can help deal with this.

During training, the model is evaluated on a holdout validation dataset after each epoch. If the performance of the model on the validation dataset starts to degrade or there is no improvement (e.g. loss begins to increase or accuracy begins to decrease), then the training process is stopped after the certian amount of interations. The model at the time that training is stopped is then used and is known to have good generalization performance.

This procedure is called early stopping and is perhaps one of the oldest and most widely used forms of neural network regularization.

Weight Initialization¶

Weight initialization is an important consideration in the design of a neural network model.

The nodes in neural networks are composed of parameters referred to as weights used to calculate a weighted sum of the inputs.

Neural network models are fit using an optimization algorithm called stochastic gradient descent that incrementally changes the network weights to minimize a loss function, hopefully resulting in a set of weights for the node that is capable of making useful predictions.

This optimization algorithm requires a starting point in the space of possible weight values from which to begin the optimization process. Weight initialization is a procedure to set the weights of a neural network to small random values that define the starting point for the optimization (learning or training) of the neural network model.

There are many WI techniques as follows:

1) Random normal initialization

2) Random Uniform initialization

3) Xaviour Initialization

4) He Initialization

Weighted loss to account for large class imbalance in train dataset¶

We will adjust the class imbalance by giving additional weight to the loss associated to errors made on churned customers. We will use our first ANN model and apply weighted loss

Let's review the process:

In [57]:
from sklearn.utils import class_weight
class_weights = class_weight.compute_class_weight('balanced', np.unique(y_train), np.array([y_train.iloc[i] for i in range(len(y_train))]))
class_weights = dict(enumerate(class_weights))
class_weights

The class 'Exited' (y=1) is assigned a weight of 2.46 vs 0.627 for the class 'Not Exited' due to the very low prevalence we detected during data exploration. This allows the model to give more importance to the errors made on fraudulent cases during training.

Insights:¶

Making use of weighted loss has helped with the performace of the model.The recall for the model has increased significantly to 0.776 and the percentage of false negatives has reduced to just 4.60%. The model is now much better are being able to predict customers that have churned. The weighted model is the best of the models we have implemented thus far. We will therefore look to revaulate and improve the performance of this model by forms of hyper parameter tuning.

Hyper Paramter Tuning¶

Finding the optimal batch and epcoh hyper-parameter values to use can be difficult. The goal is to continuously minimize the loss. For our case at hand, we want the model that will minmize this loss, so that we can maximize the recall and minimize the false negatives.

To find the optimal model use trial and error using different hyperparameter values and see what are the optimal results.

Model Performance Evaluation¶

  • Evaluate the model on different performance metrics and comment on the performance and scope of improvement

Referring to the previously computed confusion matrix of this model (epoch of 100 and batch size of 8), this model has the lowest number of false negatives with just 4.3%, meaning the model incorrectly predicted 86 customers had not churned. This is substantially less than the origional model that was computed, with 218 false negatives (10.9%). In addition, the recall is considerably higher for this hyper tuned model, at 79.1%. This is a considerable increase from the origional neural network model computed, which had a recall of just 47%.

Initially, as previously discussed there was significant imbalance in the data, with roughly 80% of customers havings stayed with the bank. Therefore without treating this imbalance, the outcome is going to be biased towards the dominant class. The use of weighted loss places more importance on the less dominant class i.e. churned customers in this case. The class 'Exited' (y=1) is assigned a weight of 2.46 vs 0.627 for the class 'Not Exited' due to the very low prevalence we detected during data exploration. This allows the model to give more importance to the errors made on churned customers during training.

Taking this approach reduces the chances of bias significantly. However, despite the recall having improved, the precision is still quite low, with a high percentage of false positives. Despite precision not being the primary metric of concern, further evaluation and testing would be advised in order to assess if futher improvements could be made. Precison should not be considered a useless metric, as it is still of importance for the bank. For example, if the bank were to predict a high percentage of customers would churn, but they stayed, customer satisfaction be be low. This may be due to the bank not being very engaged with these customers and not providing any new promotions to these customers. In the future, customer disatisfaction may result in the customers leaving. As mentioned in EDA, France has the highest amount of customers. However, both Spain & Germany have a higher percentage of their customers exiting the bank. Customer satisfaction and further engagement from the bank, may be an advisable scope for improvement in these areas.

On the contrary, if the bank were to predict that a high percentage of customers will leave the bank, they may actually waist resources trying to convinve these customers to stay with the bank.

Further Improvements¶

Different forms of hyper parmeter tuning could be used, with various other types of models e.g. Random Forests, Decision Trees and other forms of Ensemble techniques. Further hyper parameter tuning on these models, utilizing hyper parameters such as min sample leaf, max features and max samples, would be advisable.

While we did look to cater to the imbalance of the data using weighted loss, other approachs such as resampling the data could have been take. Using Synthetic Minority Oversampling Techniques (SMOTE), such as upsampling and downsampling are examples of appraoches that could be taken.

While implementing other methods and revaluating the performance on these new models is advised, implmenting some of these techniques is computationally exhaustive. We therefore will not be implemeting them for the purpose of this assignement. Additional approaches would be recommended for hypertuning the models that we have developed, to see if improvements could be made. However, there is no direct way to calculate how a change in the hyperparameter value will reduce the loss of your model until you try those hyperparameters. Therefore additional testing would be advised, but not for this project given the time on our hands.

Conclusion:¶

Overall, we did manage to improve the performance of the model. We have improved the ability for for the model to correctly predict customers that will exit the bank. From our results the Recall has increased but the precision is quite low. There is still lot of scope of improvements as follows:

2) Resampling techniques can be applied to balanced the data and then train the model

3) Hyperparameter tuning can be applied to tune the different Hyperparameters

We can select the weighted loss model as our model of best fit. With some hyperparameter tuning, we were able to further improve the performance of this model. However, additional training, different forms of resampling and even analysing with different models would be advised.

Lastly, we have based the performance of these models purely around recall. For a bank being to identify the customers who will churn, versus those that will not churn, is deemed the best metric to use. However, precision is a metric that should not be perceived as useless. Reason being, the bank may spend and waist a lot of resources on customers that will predict will churn, but they in fact stay with the bank.
